1
00:00:07,040 --> 00:00:08,000
CHAPTER ONE

2
00:00:09,360 --> 00:00:11,200
The New Computer System

3
00:00:14,080 --> 00:00:18,160
At exactly 8.20 Mr Henry Williams 
walked through the doors of the bank.  

4
00:00:19,520 --> 00:00:25,760
He was the manager and had worked there for twenty 
years. He wasn't always calm and relaxed when  

5
00:00:25,760 --> 00:00:30,640
he arrived at work but yesterday something 
had happened to make his life much easier.  

6
00:00:32,080 --> 00:00:37,360
He looked around the bank. There were 
beautiful new computers on every desk.

7
00:00:38,560 --> 00:00:46,240
Some were connected to printers, others to 
scanners. The CPUs were hidden under the desks  

8
00:00:46,240 --> 00:00:52,720
and the keyboards waited to be used. On each 
mouse pad was a mouse with a small red light,  

9
00:00:52,720 --> 00:00:59,280
which lit up when the computer was switched on. 
The VDUs shone as the sun came through the window.  

10
00:01:00,320 --> 00:01:06,800
Mr Williams smiled. When he entered his office, 
he saw that his secretary had already arrived.

11
00:01:06,800 --> 00:01:14,400
"Morning, Mr Williams," she said happily. She 
was a very nice girl with long, blonde hair  

12
00:01:14,400 --> 00:01:19,280
and a big smile but she wasn't the 
most efficient secretary in the world.

13
00:01:19,280 --> 00:01:22,000
"Good morning, Belinda. Are you looking forward to  

14
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:25,360
discovering the wonderful things 
that your new computer can do?"

15
00:01:25,360 --> 00:01:30,320
She looked worried. "Yes, but I 
hope I don't make too many mistakes.  

16
00:01:30,320 --> 00:01:34,480
Yesterday I nearly lost some important 
information because I pressed the wrong key."

17
00:01:35,120 --> 00:01:41,600
"Don't worry. I know you've only been here for six 
months. Mike has assured me that we now have the  

18
00:01:41,600 --> 00:01:46,960
most up-to-date computer hardware and software 
are the most secure system money can buy."

19
00:01:47,760 --> 00:01:51,760
Mike Black was the bank's network 
manager and head of technology.  

20
00:01:52,720 --> 00:01:55,520
He had organized and set up the new system.

21
00:01:57,520 --> 00:02:01,920
At that moment someone knocked 
on the door and Mike came in.

22
00:02:02,480 --> 00:02:06,160
"Morning, Mr Williams. How are you?" he said.

23
00:02:06,160 --> 00:02:10,960
"Very well, thank you, Mike. Now, are you 
sure the system is functioning properly? Can  

24
00:02:10,960 --> 00:02:14,880
I go on holiday next week to the Caribbean 
without worrying about things back here?"

25
00:02:14,880 --> 00:02:20,880
Mike smiled. "Things couldn't be better. 
Our LAN is working perfectly. It is now  

26
00:02:20,880 --> 00:02:24,480
connected to the bank's WAN and 
the security access rights are..."

27
00:02:24,480 --> 00:02:28,240
"Mike, you know that my knowledge of 
computers is very limited. I'm afraid  

28
00:02:28,240 --> 00:02:33,120
I belong to another generation - which is 
why I pay you to solve our IT problems."

29
00:02:33,120 --> 00:02:40,000
IT terms were a foreign language to Henry 
Williams. His son Robbie was only 15 but  

30
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:45,040
he was already a computer genius and sat in 
front of his monitor for hours every day.  

31
00:02:46,160 --> 00:02:53,360
He had no problem logging on and off, surfing 
the net or downloading files. His father was an  

32
00:02:53,360 --> 00:02:58,000
excellent bank manager but unfortunately 
he had no idea what these terms meant.  

33
00:02:58,800 --> 00:03:03,760
He was grateful for experts like Mike who 
could decipher these mysteries for him.

34
00:03:03,760 --> 00:03:04,960
"Don't worry.  

35
00:03:04,960 --> 00:03:10,160
You can have a wonderful time in the Caribbean. 
Things couldn't be better here," replied Mike.

36
00:03:10,800 --> 00:03:13,040
He left the office and Mr Williams sat down  

37
00:03:13,040 --> 00:03:17,840
at his desk on which there was no 
computer at all, either new or old.

38
00:03:18,400 --> 00:03:23,040
He was dreaming of blue seas and white 
beaches when a cry from Belinda's desk  

39
00:03:23,040 --> 00:03:29,440
brought him back to reality. "Mr Williams, my 
computer has crashed!" As soon as she had said  

40
00:03:29,440 --> 00:03:34,480
the words, they heard similar cries of alarm 
coming from the bank's main area downstairs.

41
00:03:35,360 --> 00:03:45,840
One by one the computers were crashing...
 
 

42
00:03:47,280 --> 00:03:48,160
CHAPTER TWO

43
00:03:49,440 --> 00:03:50,160
A Problem

44
00:03:52,080 --> 00:03:55,920
Mr Williams ran down the escalator 
and into the main office area.  

45
00:03:55,920 --> 00:03:59,840
What was happening? All the computers 
were down. Everyone was trying to reboot  

46
00:04:00,480 --> 00:04:06,560
but it was impossible. Henry Williams tried 
not to panic. He asked Belinda to call Mike  

47
00:04:06,560 --> 00:04:11,120
and tell him to come immediately. Then he 
said to his staff, "Don't worry, everyone.  

48
00:04:11,760 --> 00:04:17,360
I'm sure it's a minor problem that Mike will 
soon resolve." A young bank teller whispered to  

49
00:04:17,360 --> 00:04:23,200
a colleague, "He said that last week when that 
virus destroyed most of our files. Remember?"

50
00:04:24,320 --> 00:04:30,160
His friend smiled. Someone had sent an e-mail to 
all the staff which promised to show photos of  

51
00:04:30,160 --> 00:04:36,960
Belinda's new boyfriend. Belinda was very popular 
with the staff in the bank so naturally everyone  

52
00:04:36,960 --> 00:04:42,800
opened it. But there was no photo, just a 
virus which corrupted the entire system.  

53
00:04:44,240 --> 00:04:48,560
Mike, who still didn't know about the problem, 
arrived in the lift just as strange things began  

54
00:04:48,560 --> 00:04:54,320
to happen. First the lights went off, leaving 
the bank in darkness. Then a client came in to  

55
00:04:54,320 --> 00:05:00,400
complain to a cashier that he couldn't access 
his account from the ATM outside the bank. Then  

56
00:05:00,400 --> 00:05:07,360
the lights came on again but the doors closed 
automatically, locking everyone in the bank.  

57
00:05:09,120 --> 00:05:16,000
Mr Williams said sarcastically, "As you can see, 
Mike, our new system is working perfectly. Nobody  

58
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:20,000
can do any work, the clients are angry, 
and we are all prisoners in the bank!"

59
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:24,800
Mike smiled nervously. "I'm sure it's 
nothing. I'll take a look at the server  

60
00:05:24,800 --> 00:05:30,160
and see what the problem is." Mike was the 
only person with total security access rights  

61
00:05:30,160 --> 00:05:34,160
for the system and he had the 
only copy of the password list.  

62
00:05:35,120 --> 00:05:38,720
He was very good at his job so 
he wasn't too worried about these  

63
00:05:38,720 --> 00:05:45,920
"hiccups." He went to the main computer and put 
in his password. A message appeared on the screen:

64
00:05:46,640 --> 00:05:47,680
Access Denied

65
00:05:48,240 --> 00:05:49,920
Password Invalid

66
00:05:49,920 --> 00:05:55,520
Everyone in the bank was watching him. Mike took 
his password list from his wallet. He typed in  

67
00:05:55,520 --> 00:06:03,920
his password again, slowly and carefully. Every 
time he tried the same message appeared on the  

68
00:06:03,920 --> 00:06:10,480
screen. "That's impossible," he cried. His face 
was white with tension. Mr Williams was waiting  

69
00:06:10,480 --> 00:06:17,280
for an explanation. "Is everything OK?" he asked. 
Mike prepared to give his boss the bad news.

70
00:06:18,080 --> 00:06:22,080
"It seems that... someone has obtained 
the passwords for the new system  

71
00:06:22,800 --> 00:06:24,880
and... has changed them."

72
00:06:24,880 --> 00:06:30,800
"And what exactly does that mean?" asked 
his boss angrily. Mike took a deep breath.

73
00:06:31,920 --> 00:06:35,760
"It means that this person now 
has total control of the bank."

74
00:06:35,760 --> 00:06:38,880
At that moment the doors of the 
bank miraculously opened again.  

75
00:06:39,920 --> 00:06:47,840
No one spoke. The silence was broken only 
by the noise of the clock on the wall.  

76
00:06:50,480 --> 00:06:53,200
All the staff were waiting 
for Mr Williams' reaction.

77
00:06:53,200 --> 00:06:59,040
"And tell me, how did this person get the 
passwords?" asked Mr Williams quietly.

78
00:06:59,040 --> 00:07:04,640
"I have no idea," replied Mike. "I always 
keep the password list in my wallet.  

79
00:07:05,520 --> 00:07:09,280
No one else has ever seen 
it. It's a complete mystery."

80
00:07:09,280 --> 00:07:13,280
"No!" shouted Mr Williams. "The 
mystery is why I gave you a  

81
00:07:13,280 --> 00:07:18,960
job. First the virus and now this. Well, you 
can start looking for a new job. You're sacked!"

82
00:07:18,960 --> 00:07:24,240
Mike left the bank without a word. He didn't 
look at anyone. He knew that it was his fault.  

83
00:07:25,520 --> 00:07:30,160
Belinda's voice broke the silence. 
"Oh, Mr Williams, what are we going to  

84
00:07:30,160 --> 00:07:34,800
do?" Before he could answer, the 
computer displayed a new message:

85
00:07:35,680 --> 00:07:43,840
E-mail arriving for Henry Williams
 
 

86
00:07:48,320 --> 00:07:49,280
CHAPTER THREE

87
00:07:51,200 --> 00:07:53,360
Are You Ready to Play, Henry?

88
00:07:54,800 --> 00:07:57,600
Mr Williams turned to the bank staff and said,  

89
00:07:57,600 --> 00:08:01,680
"Please, continue to work as normal. 
There is nothing to worry about."

90
00:08:02,480 --> 00:08:09,120
Everyone looked surprised. How could they work 
without computers? It would be impossible. No one  

91
00:08:09,120 --> 00:08:14,480
moved and no one spoke. Mr Williams repeated 
his message: "Back to work now, please.  

92
00:08:15,280 --> 00:08:21,200
Our clients will arrive soon and we must be 
ready." As his staff slowly began to return  

93
00:08:21,200 --> 00:08:26,720
to work, the bank manager sat down in front 
of the server. Belinda stood next to him.  

94
00:08:27,280 --> 00:08:33,680
Mr Williams looked at the screen. He was now 
extremely worried. He hesitated for a moment.  

95
00:08:34,560 --> 00:08:39,360
Belinda thought he was in difficulty and she 
wanted to help. "You have to click on the e-mail  

96
00:08:39,360 --> 00:08:44,640
icon in the comer of the screen," she said. "I 
know, I know. I'm not completely stupid!" her  

97
00:08:44,640 --> 00:08:52,880
boss shouted. Some members of staff looked at one 
another and smiled. Belinda knew Mr Williams well.  

98
00:08:53,680 --> 00:09:01,280
She knew that when he was angry, as he was now, it 
was better to say nothing. She watched silently as  

99
00:09:01,280 --> 00:09:08,320
he clicked on the icon. The mailbox appeared 
and revealed the subject of the new message:

100
00:09:08,320 --> 00:09:10,960
Are you ready to play, Henry Williams?

101
00:09:12,240 --> 00:09:18,080
Yes, he was ready. He had no idea who had 
sent the e-mail but he wanted an explanation  

102
00:09:18,080 --> 00:09:23,920
and an end to this situation. He opened the 
message and the screen filled with words.

103
00:09:25,360 --> 00:09:26,240
Hello Henry!

104
00:09:26,800 --> 00:09:31,920
How are you today? Happy? Or 
maybe worried? Or even angry!  

105
00:09:33,040 --> 00:09:39,280
I haven't seen you for a long time but I can 
tell you that I am very, very annoyed with you.  

106
00:09:40,240 --> 00:09:49,360
You are not my favorite person. How many enemies 
do you have? AT least one - me! I am going to  

107
00:09:49,360 --> 00:09:57,680
make you pay for what you did to me before. As you 
know, I have entered your new and secure (ha! ha!)  

108
00:09:57,680 --> 00:10:05,520
computer system and guess what? It's MY system 
now. It was so easy to discover the passwords.  

109
00:10:06,240 --> 00:10:11,360
You should be more careful, Henry. You 
don't mind if I call you Henry, do you?

110
00:10:13,040 --> 00:10:17,840
Mr Williams was definitely angry 
now, and confused. He asked Belinda,  

111
00:10:18,480 --> 00:10:24,000
"Who is this person? What does he want? Or maybe 
it's a woman? Why is he (or she) angry? I'm an  

112
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:28,480
honest and respectable man and people like me 
- well, most people. Isn't that true, Belinda?"  

113
00:10:29,200 --> 00:10:32,960
He turned to look at Belinda, hoping that she 
would give him the answer he wanted to hear,  

114
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:38,080
but she wasn't listening. She was reading 
the rest of the message as it appeared...

115
00:10:39,520 --> 00:10:46,320
I have changed all the passwords so now I 
control everything in your bank. Be nice to me  

116
00:10:46,320 --> 00:10:53,360
or I will lock the door again - or perhaps I'll 
do something much worse! But don't be afraid;  

117
00:10:54,080 --> 00:10:59,760
I know that you're an intelligent (ha! 
ha!) man, Henry, so I am going to give  

118
00:10:59,760 --> 00:11:06,480
you a chance to save your precious bank. 
We are going to play a game. If you win,  

119
00:11:06,480 --> 00:11:13,840
the bank will be saved. If you lose... the 
bank will be destroyed! Do you like my idea?  

120
00:11:14,720 --> 00:11:21,520
I think it's great! It means that the fate 
of the bank, your bank, is in your own hands.

121
00:11:22,480 --> 00:11:27,840
So, Henry, my friend... are you ready to play?
 
 

122
00:11:35,760 --> 00:11:36,640
CHAPTER FOUR

123
00:11:38,080 --> 00:11:39,600
Don't Call the Police!

124
00:11:40,720 --> 00:11:45,440
It was very noisy in the bank. Clients were 
arriving and the staff had to tell them that  

125
00:11:45,440 --> 00:11:52,000
there was a problem with the computers. Some 
clients left immediately, some were angry and  

126
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:57,680
began to shout, others wanted to see the manager. 
But Mr Williams had no time to speak to anyone.  

127
00:11:58,240 --> 00:12:04,160
He had a problem too. A big problem. Two members 
of his staff had moved the server to his office.  

128
00:12:04,160 --> 00:12:07,600
It was much quieter in there and he could 
think without anyone disturbing him.

129
00:12:09,840 --> 00:12:13,200
Belinda was sitting next to 
him. She was beginning to panic  

130
00:12:13,200 --> 00:12:15,760
and when she felt like that 
she couldn't stop talking.

131
00:12:16,480 --> 00:12:19,520
"What a horrible man. I'm sure it's a man.  

132
00:12:19,520 --> 00:12:24,320
He's so evil. What are you going to do, 
Mr Williams? What a terrible situation!  

133
00:12:24,320 --> 00:12:28,400
I want to help you but I just don't know what 
to do. Shall we call the police? I'm sure..."

134
00:12:28,400 --> 00:12:32,880
Mr Williams couldn't concentrate. His 
secretary was talking faster and faster.

135
00:12:32,880 --> 00:12:36,880
"Belinda, why don't you go and 
make me a nice cup of tea?"

136
00:12:37,520 --> 00:12:39,920
Belinda smiled brightly 
and went out of the office.  

137
00:12:40,800 --> 00:12:44,160
A nice cup of tea was the solution 
to all problems in her opinion.

138
00:12:45,440 --> 00:12:50,480
So, undisturbed, Mr Williams was able to 
read the final part of the mysterious e-mail.

139
00:12:51,520 --> 00:12:55,600
This is the game: I will send you three puzzles,  

140
00:12:55,600 --> 00:13:00,880
one at a time. You must solve 
these puzzles in just 24 hours.

141
00:13:01,840 --> 00:13:08,000
That's plenty of time for an intelligent man 
like you, Henry. You'll probably need to be a  

142
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:15,680
computer expert to solve them, but you use 
computers every day, don't you? (Ha! ha!)  

143
00:13:15,680 --> 00:13:22,080
If you fail to solve all three puzzles, I 
will empty every bank account in your bank  

144
00:13:22,080 --> 00:13:29,600
from the smallest to the largest. all the money 
will disappear and your bank will be destroyed.

145
00:13:31,360 --> 00:13:36,960
One final thing - DON'T call the 
police. That would be very stupid.  

146
00:13:38,800 --> 00:13:41,120
If you call the police, I will know.

147
00:13:42,160 --> 00:13:48,240
Remember that I can destroy your bank 
in a few seconds. Don't risk it, Henry.

148
00:13:49,360 --> 00:13:54,880
Do you think this is all a joke? I want 
to show you that I am very serious.  

149
00:13:55,920 --> 00:14:01,840
Henry, do you know how much money you 
have in your bank account? Are you sure?

150
00:14:03,200 --> 00:14:06,880
Why don't you check? I think you'll be surprised!

151
00:14:08,560 --> 00:14:14,480
Now I am going to give your staff access to the 
computers so the bank can function as normal.  

152
00:14:15,520 --> 00:14:17,520
You see, I'm not so evil,  

153
00:14:18,800 --> 00:14:24,560
but remember that I can switch off the 
computers or change anything at any time.

154
00:14:25,840 --> 00:14:30,240
Bye for now, but don't worry... I'll be back soon.

155
00:14:31,600 --> 00:14:38,720
Mr Williams sat back in his chair. He had a 
bad headache. Things were not improving. He was  

156
00:14:38,720 --> 00:14:43,840
thinking about what to do when he heard shouts 
of joy coming from the bank staff downstairs.  

157
00:14:49,760 --> 00:14:51,840
The door opened and Belinda came in with the tea.  

158
00:14:54,560 --> 00:14:57,840
"The computers are working again, 
Mr Williams. Isn't that wonderful?  

159
00:14:58,640 --> 00:15:02,320
Everything is back to normal. 
Maybe the e-mail was just a joke."

160
00:15:03,120 --> 00:15:09,120
"Well, we'll know in a moment, Belinda," 
he replied. There were two things that  

161
00:15:09,120 --> 00:15:15,120
Mr Williams could do on a computer - use 
e-mail and access his own bank account.  

162
00:15:16,400 --> 00:15:23,040
Why did the mystery hacker tell him to check 
his account? He put in his password and then his  

163
00:15:23,040 --> 00:15:28,720
account number and waited. After a few seconds the 
information he wanted appeared on the screen...
 
 

164
00:15:38,240 --> 00:15:39,360
CHAPTER FIVE

165
00:15:40,720 --> 00:15:42,160
Puzzle Number One

166
00:15:44,400 --> 00:15:47,280
Mr Williams stared at the 
computer screen, horrified.  

167
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:53,440
His hank account was empty! The 
bank manager quickly closed the page  

168
00:15:53,440 --> 00:15:59,360
but Belinda had already seen it. She 
dropped her cup of tea and began to cry.  

169
00:16:04,160 --> 00:16:07,840
Before Henry Williams could say a word, 
another message appeared on the screen.

170
00:16:09,120 --> 00:16:13,120
E-mail arriving for Henry 
Williams Puzzle Number One

171
00:16:14,480 --> 00:16:18,080
Mr Williams clicked to open the 
message and looked at the first puzzle.  

172
00:16:19,520 --> 00:16:23,760
There were just a few words and lots 
of strange symbols and abbreviations.

173
00:16:24,560 --> 00:16:26,800
It's 9.15 and time to play!

174
00:16:27,600 --> 00:16:30,240
